\section{Shared Abstractions}\label{sec:sys:shared}

\paragraph{Graph state.}
Every configuration is a LangGraph \texttt{StateGraph} over a shared
\texttt{GraphState} object (Listing~\ref{lst:state}). Using a shared schema enforces
configuration parity: no configuration has access to fields another lacks, and the
JSONL persistence format is identical across all five configurations.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={GraphState schema (abridged from
  \texttt{src/agents/state.py}).}, label={lst:state},
  basicstyle=\footnotesize\ttfamily, frame=single]
class GraphState(TypedDict, total=False):
    # Inputs (unchanged throughout graph)
    contract_text:      str
    category:           str   # one of 41 CUAD category names
    question:           str   # CUAD annotation-guideline question text

    # Routing (set by orchestrator node --- M1 only)
    specialist_name:    str   # "risk_liability" | "temporal_renewal" | "ip_commercial"

    # Extraction (set by specialist or baseline node)
    extraction_result:  ExtractionResult | None

    # Validation (set by validation node)
    validated:          bool
    validation_notes:   str

    # Final output
    final_result:       ExtractionResult | None

    # Trace: append-reducer accumulates entries across all nodes
    trace: Annotated[list[dict[str, Any]], append_trace]

    error: str | None
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{Prompt registry.}
Prompts are stored as YAML and loaded once per run; the schema version hash is
written to the run metadata so prompt drift is detectable post-hoc. Two roots:
\texttt{prompts/baselines/} (B0, B4, and the M0 classifier and extractor) and
\texttt{prompts/specialists/} (the three M1 domain specialists and the M6
consolidated prompt). A shared \texttt{system/} directory holds anti-laziness
instructions and the verbatim-span output contract, referenced by all configurations,
ensuring that the anti-laziness and verbatim-span output instructions are identical
across B0, B4, M0, M1, and M6.

\paragraph{Common parser.}
A single parser converts every model completion to a canonical
\texttt{(spans: list[str]~|~None)} representation. For B0, the parser accepts
verbatim quoted spans or the literal string ``no related clause''. For B4 and
M0-extractor, the parser additionally requires a \texttt{<answer>...</answer>} tag
and issues a single repair re-prompt if the tag is absent. On persistent failure the
record is marked \texttt{parser\_status="rejected"} and excluded from official
statistics (1{,}297 of 164{,}941 predictions, $0.79\%$).

\section{Baseline Architectures}\label{sec:sys:baselines}

\paragraph{B0 --- Zero-shot single agent.}
B0 replicates the zero-shot prompt protocol of~\cite{liu2025contracteval}. The model
receives one user message containing the contract text, the target category name, the
category indicator, and an explicit instruction to return verbatim span(s) or the
literal string ``no related clause''. No examples, no chain-of-thought directives.

\begin{promptbox}{B0: zero-shot user template}
You are reviewing a commercial contract. Determine whether the contract contains
any clause(s) of the category below. If yes, return the verbatim span(s); each span
must appear exactly as in the contract. If no, return exactly: ``no related clause''.

\textbf{Category:} \{\{category\}\} \quad
\textbf{Description:} \{\{category\_indicator\}\}

\textbf{Contract:} \{\{contract\_text\}\}
\end{promptbox}

\paragraph{B4 --- Chain-of-thought single agent.}
B4 retains B0's task framing but elicits explicit step-by-step reasoning before a
final structured answer. The model is instructed to restate what the category covers,
scan for candidate spans, weigh ambiguous matches against the indicator, and emit a
final \texttt{<answer>...</answer>} block. A parsing bug in pilot work caused
contract passages quoted inside the chain-of-thought to be harvested as answers,
inflating $\omega$ (Eq.~\ref{eq:overextract}); the fix enforces the answer tag via
the common parser of Section~\ref{sec:sys:shared}. The fix was deployed in commit
\texttt{[TODO: insert commit hash]} on \textbf{[TODO: insert date]}; only post-fix
runs enter official statistics.

\section{Multi-Agent Architectures}\label{sec:sys:multiagent}

\paragraph{M0 --- Classify-then-extract.}
M0 decomposes each (contract, category) task into two sequential LLM calls. The
\emph{classifier} returns a single yes/no token; the \emph{extractor} is invoked
only if the classifier returns yes. The two agents share the category indicator but
have disjoint prompts: the classifier is forbidden to emit spans, the extractor
assumes presence. Listing~\ref{lst:m0-prompts} excerpts both prompts;
Listing~\ref{lst:m0-graph} shows the LangGraph construction. Non-binary classifier
responses (e.g.\ capitalised ``Yes'', punctuated ``no.'', or free-form text) are
normalised by case-folding and stripping punctuation before matching; responses that
do not resolve to ``yes'' or ``no'' after normalisation are treated as ``no'' and the
record is flagged \texttt{parser\_status="rejected"}, contributing to the 1{,}297
excluded predictions ($0.79\%$).

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={M0 classifier and extractor prompts (abridged).},
  label={lst:m0-prompts}, basicstyle=\footnotesize\ttfamily, frame=single]
# --- classifier ---
Decide whether the contract contains any clause of the category below.
Return exactly one token: "yes" or "no". Do not return spans.
Category: {{category}}   Description: {{category_indicator}}
Contract: {{contract_text}}

# --- extractor (invoked only when classifier returned "yes") ---
The contract contains at least one clause of the category below.
Return the verbatim span(s) wrapped in <answer>...</answer>.
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={M0 LangGraph construction.},
  label={lst:m0-graph}, basicstyle=\footnotesize\ttfamily,
  keywordstyle=\bfseries\color{TUMBlue}, frame=single]
g = StateGraph(GraphState)
g.add_node("classify", classify_node)
g.add_node("extract",  extract_node)
g.set_entry_point("classify")
g.add_conditional_edges(
    "classify",
    lambda s: "extract" if s["classifier_verdict"] == "yes" else END,
    {"extract": "extract", END: END},
)
g.add_edge("extract", END)
\end{lstlisting}

