      "completion": "<answer>The aggregate liability ... shall not exceed ...</answer>",
      "tokens_in":  14820, "tokens_out": 96,
      "latency_ms": 4210,  "cost_usd": 0.0470,
      "parent_id":  "router" }
  ],
  "final_answer":  "The aggregate liability ... shall not exceed ...",
  "parser_status": "ok"
}
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{Auditability properties.}
The trace structure supports three concrete properties. \emph{Decision attribution}:
any final answer is traceable to the specific agent, prompt version, and model that
produced it. \emph{Counterfactual replay}: because prompts and model identifiers are
pinned per call at \texttt{temperature=0}, a reviewer can re-run a single archived
call and obtain a deterministically identical completion. \emph{Rejection forensics}:
when M0 silently returns ``no related clause'', the classifier's verdict is recorded
explicitly, making the classification-gate cascade of Section~\ref{sec:res:cascade}
visible at audit time as an upstream rejection rather than an unobservable absence.

\paragraph{Trade-offs and limits.}
The JSONL persistence layer is on the order of gigabytes per full sweep, and trace
fields containing rendered prompts and full completions inherit the contract's
confidentiality classification. The system distinguishes between decision-level fields
(configuration, verdict, token counts) safe to surface to operators, and
content-level fields (rendered prompts, full completions) that are access-controlled.
The trace is faithful to the call graph, not to the model's internal computation:
a chain-of-thought trace records what the model emitted, not what it computed.

\paragraph{Trace completeness.}
Trace completeness --- the fraction of model calls for which all expected fields are
populated --- was $100\%$ for B0, B4, and M6 (single-call configurations with no
routing decisions), $100\%$ for M0 (two-call pipeline with deterministic branching),
and $95.2\%$ for M1 across official runs. The binding constraint is M1: the remaining
$4.8\%$ are provider-side truncations on long contracts and are flagged in the run
logs. The single-configuration baseline ($100\%$) confirms that the drop is
attributable to M1's multi-call routing overhead, not to infrastructure failures.

\section{Experimental Infrastructure}\label{sec:sys:infra}

\paragraph{Loader and sampler.}
The CUAD loader is the single source of truth for which contracts and categories
enter a run. It applies the 100{,}000-character filter, the \texttt{neg\_ratio=0.7}
natural-prior sampler of Section~\ref{sec:meth:sampling}, and the prevalence-tier
partition. It is deterministic under \texttt{seed=42} and produces the identical
$\approx\!2{,}999$-sample envelope across all five configurations, making paired
tests in Chapter~\ref{chapter:results} well-defined at the (contract, category)
level.

\paragraph{Statistical aggregation.}
A separate aggregation pipeline reads per-run JSONL outputs, computes per-sample
correctness vectors, and emits the McNemar contingency tables, paired bootstrap
distributions, and BH-corrected $p$-value tables of Section~\ref{sec:meth:stats}.
Aggregation is deterministic given the JSONL inputs and a fixed bootstrap seed;
intermediate artefacts are persisted so results can be regenerated without
rerunning models.

\paragraph{Dashboard.}
A Next.js dashboard supports interactive exploration: per-model $F_2$ comparisons,
per-tier breakdowns, per-call cost and latency views, and trace inspection by sample
ID. The over-extraction failure mode in Chapter~\ref{chapter:results} was first
surfaced visually through the dashboard's per-category $\omega$ panel.

\paragraph{Test suite and repository layout.}
An 81-test suite covers the metric implementations ($F_1$/$F_2$, Jaccard, $\lambda$,
$\omega$), the loader (filter, sampling determinism, tier assignment), the agent
topologies (each of B0, B4, M0, M1, M6 has at least one end-to-end test against a
stub model), and the statistical pipelines (McNemar, bootstrap, BH correction).
The full suite passes prior to every official run. The repository is organised as in
Listing~\ref{lst:repo}.

